<TEXT>
eighteen university students and a teacher held a 
brief sitin sunday in tiananmen square to demand more money for 
education and better living standards for intellectuals 
a western reporter who witnessed the sitin at the capitals 
center said several dozen uniformed police politely asked 
passersby to give room to the protesters and said they had the 
right to express their view 
the reporter said the protesters were just sitting there 
quietly with a small sign in chinese and english saying we want 
more money for education 
the sitin began at about 1 pm and ended about 230 pm when 
the group apparently left on its own he said it attracted only a 
small crowd in the huge square jammed with chinese enjoying the 
warm weather and flying kites 
the protest capped a week of complaints from students that the 
government is not investing enough money in education 
both the nonpolitical tone of the protests and the mild 
official response is in sharp contrast to the nationwide student 
protests in the winter of 198687 when students issued sweeping 
calls for democracy and the state responded by jailing student 
leaders 
in a rare report of dissent in china the official xinhua news 
agency mentioned the student sitin but specified that the demands 
were in line with comments made in the past two weeks by delegates 
to the national peoples congress and chinese peoples political 
consultative conference 
the national peoples congress chinas legislature and the 
consultative conference an advisory body are holding their annual 
sessions in beijing 
delegates at both have stressed the need for more attention to 
education and for higher salaries for teachers and other 
intellectuals who generally are paid less than factory workers 
xinhua said the sitin participants came from beijing 
university qinghua university and beijing teachers university 
the xinhua report quoted officials as saying funds for education 
would increase 122 percent this year over last and that the state 
had made a big effort to budget money for education at a time 
when the country has many financial difficulties 
