<TEXT>
an outspoken soviet economist says mikhail s 
gorbachevs reform effort is being jeopardized by hostile local 
officials and suspicious consumers who fear theyll suffer for any 
progress 
nikolai shmelev wrote in the april edition of the literary 
journal novy mir that key agricultural reforms have completely 
failed he also criticized some of gorbachevs initiatives 
he said the soviet leaders antidrinking campaign has done 
little but make moonshiners rich and that officials are misguided 
in trying to restructure the economy and accelerate growth at the 
same time 
shmelev proposed a deeper reform of farming an increase in 
imported food and consumer goods and better use of soviet 
financial reserves 
the criticism in the article and shmelevs previous scathing 
attack on the soviet economy published in last junes novy mir 
are among the sharpest made publicly by a soviet economist 
it is impossible not to see that a hidden opposition to 
perestroika restructuring is growing in the regions from the side 
of many local party government and economic officials shmelev 
said 
the economist said that while they pay lip service to 
gorbachevs reforms a silent conspiracy against him could be 
developing or may already have developed among local officials and 
bureaucrats in moscow 
gorbachev needs some successes in the near future to show that 
his program is working but his rural opponents have paralyzed the 
system shmelev charged 
in rallying support for his reforms gorbachev has put pressure 
on local and central bureacrats and blamed them for slowing the 
progress of his restructuring effort 
but gorbachev also has noted that soviets still have seen little 
improvement in the quality or supply of food or consumer goods 
shmelev said promises that food prices will go up have 
frightened many soviets into thinking the reforms will hurt them 
he said that fear results from the way government agencies have 
operated in the past 
officials who have promised that they will increase benefits 
and wages to match price increases must make an allout effort to 
convince honest workers the elderly and those with low incomes 
that they have nothing to fear from the reforms he said 
shemelev said efforts to open more private garden plots and 
allow collective and state farms to sell some of their produce on 
the open market have failed because of local bureaucracy and the 
central governments own demands for food 
in his article last year shmelev urged that farms be allowed to 
decide for themselves how much and what kind of goods they would 
grow without any interference of state planning officials 
he said the disastrous situation of soviet agriculture is a 
result of the unlimited power that administrative layers have 
held all these decades over everything that lives in the villages 
shmelev said the effort to combat alcoholism gorbachevs first 
major initiative upon taking power in 1985 had done little but 
send millions of rubles of government income from vodka sales into 
the hands of moonshiners the soviet unions serious drinking 
problem will not be solved until consumers are offered something 
else to buy with their money he said 
gorbachev has called for increasing the quality and quantity of 
industrial and food production but shmelev said neither has 
increased and that planners were unrealistic to expected increased 
production while they were trying to restructure the foundations of 
the economy 
soviet officials have been cutting back on some imported goods 
such as coffee and tea but could make a quick improvement in 
supplies to consumers by sharply increasing such imports he said 
the soviet union could pay for such imports and strengthen 
itself economically by learning to make better use of credit 
shareholding and foreign loans and by providing better terms for 
joint ventures he said 
