<TEXT>
officials issued a public health alert after two 
families fell ill from eating cucumbers contaminated by aldicarb 
an illegal pesticide authorities said cucumbers with the 
pesticide may have been shipped to four states they said 
one case was reported in the seattle area and one in the renton 
area south of seattle state department of social and health 
services spokesman frank mendizabal said saturday the day the 
alert was issued he had no detail on the exact number of people 
involved 
roger lowell district director for the federal food and drug 
administration in seattle said it is illegal to use aldicarb on 
growing food products but its effect on health is generally 
temporary he said sunday 
the thin cucumbers 12 to 18 inches long and about 1 inches in 
diameter were grown in hothouses in northern california by barnard 
hydroponic of redding and distributed by blue anchor inc of 
sacramento lowell said 
they were distributed by wholesale channels to both independent 
and chain grocers in washington and oregon and maybe in northern 
california and idaho lowell said 
one familys illness was reported about a week ago but couldnt 
be traced to the cucumbers lowell said the second family fell ill 
thursday and laboratory tests confirmed high levels of 
contamination with aldicarb he said 
in oregon there were no reports of illness but state officials 
also issued a public health alert saturday it warned that possibly 
contaminated cucumbers had been distributed to groceries and 
restaurants throughout the state by united grocers inc and pacific 
coast fruit co said dalton hobbs public information officer for 
the state agriculture department 
bruce barnard an owner of barnard hydroponic said sunday that 
he would not comment on the situation until he had had a chance to 
talk with fda officials there was no answer at blue anchor on 
sunday 
symptoms of ingestion of aldicarb include nausea vomiting and 
diarrhea within one hour of eating lowell said other symptoms can 
include blurred vision excessive sweating and muscle twitching 
lowell said sunday that officials are unaware of any permanent 
health damage adding that the symptoms pass quickly like the flu 
in fact he said many people who may have gotten sick in the last 
week may have thought they were suffering from the flu 
aldicarb is a treatment for soil before crops are grown and is 
used mostly for nonfood crops such as cotton lowell said aldicarb 
is the same pesticide that contaminated watermelons distributed 
along the west coast two years ago 
</TEXT>
