<TEXT>
us attorney general edwin meese iii toured a 
jungle valley sunday that is the center of perus cocaineproducing 
region 
meese arrived in peru saturday following visits to the dominican 
republic colombia and ecuador as part of a weeklong tour of latin 
american nations to assess antidrug trafficking operations 
the attorney general accompanied by us and peruvian 
officials flew from lima to tocache sunday and toured the huallaga 
valley before returning to the capital 
maoist shining path guerrillas have been providing protection 
for drug traffickers in the valley for the past year and about 10 
months ago the rebels briefly controlled tocache before police 
drove them out tocache is 300 miles northeast of lima 
the huallaga valley on the junglecloaked slopes of the eastern 
andes is the major cocaleaf growing area in peru us drug 
enforcement administration officials say peru is the worlds 
largest supplier of the leaves the raw ingredient of pure cocaine 
from a helicopter meese viewed a threeacre pilot project to 
erradicate the coca plants through the use of herbicides if 
successful the method could replace the tedious system of 
uprooting the plants both erradication efforts are being funded by 
washington according the us embassy 
the united states also is partially financing police operations 
against drug traffickers in the zone and recently loaned peru 
three privately rented helicopters for drug raids 
coca leaf in peru is semiprocessed and flown to colombia where 
it is refined into pure cocaine 
meese is to meet monday with president alan garcia and hold a 
news conference before flying to bolivia where his tour will 
conclude wednesday 
