<TEXT>
the median price of a typical singlefamily 
home rose by 56 percent in 1987 with prices of similar homes 
rising in almost 86 percent of major north american markets during 
that time according to an industry survey 
the survey conducted by coldwell banker residential group the 
real estate company owned by sears roebuck and co also indicated 
the price of a similar singlefamily home in 172 markets ranged 
from 66833 in oklahoma city to 636667 in beverly hills calif 
the survey released monday reviewed sale prices of similar homes 
in 168 us and four canadian markets in december 1987 prices were 
based on three recently sold homes in each markets 
the model home was a singlefamily dwelling of about 2000 
square feet with three bedrooms two baths a family room or the 
equivalent and a twocar garage homes selected had average age 
condition curb appeal and location for a typical corporate 
transferee neighborhood in each market the survey indicated 
coldwell banker said its home price comparison index indicated 
the median home price rose 56 percent to 124900 in december 1987 
from a year earlier the median is the price point where half of 
the homes surveyed sold for less and half sold for more 
it took an average of 77 days to sell a home in 1987 with 
selling periods ranging from four days in the washington dc area 
inside the beltway or in the immediate metropolitan area to 
more than nine months in fairbanks alaska the survey indicated 
